
<div class="container" style="margin-left: 100px;">
<h1>Here we can see how we can not only create shapes using the HTML5 "canvas" tag, we can also manipulate colors and design patterns.</h1>

<div class="row" style="display: flex;">

<div class="container">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-3">
			<svg width="400" height="300">
				<defs>
    				<radialGradient id="grad3" cx="50%" cy="50%" r="50%" fx="50%" fy="50%">
      					<stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#443d41;
      						stop-opacity:0" />
      					<stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#467775;stop-opacity:1" />
    				</radialGradient>
  				</defs>
  				<rect x="50" y="20" width="250" height="150" fill="url(#grad3)";
  				style="stroke:black;stroke-width:5;" />
			</svg>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<div class="container">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-3">
			<svg width="400" height="200" style="padding-left: 100px;">
				<defs>
    			<linearGradient id="grad4" x1="0%" y1="0%" x2="100%" y2="0%">
      				<stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#06d829;stop-opacity:1" />
      				<stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#000000;stop-opacity:1" />
    			</linearGradient>
  				</defs>
  				<rect x="50" y="20" width="150" height="150" fill="url(#grad4)";/>
			</svg>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

<div class="container">
	<div class="row">
		<div class="col-md-3">
			<svg width="500" height="300" style="padding-left: 100px;">
				<defs>
    				<linearGradient id="grad5" x1="0%" y1="0%" x2="0%" y2="100%">
      					<stop offset="0%" style="stop-color:#0e3a54;stop-opacity:1" />
      					<stop offset="100%" style="stop-color:#4c98c4;stop-opacity:1" />
    				</linearGradient>
  				</defs>
  				<rect x="50" y="20" width="150" height="150" transform="rotate(45)" fill="url(#grad5)";
  				style="stroke:black;stroke-width:2;" />
			</svg>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>

</div>
</div>